WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:08.999
And the gradient of the log probability of x is exactly what we need to run gradient descent on our function.

00:09.400 --> 00:12.963
So here is our function again, g plus this regularization.

00:13.264 --> 00:16.747
Now they don't regularize over the entire future, but over these windows.

00:17.768 --> 00:21.491
But in essence, it's g plus the log probability of your plan.

00:22.052 --> 00:25.875
If you take the gradient of that, of course, you take the gradient of the sum.

00:25.956 --> 00:27.557
So it's the gradient of g.

00:27.537 --> 00:34.128
plus the gradient of the log probability with respect to the actions.

00:34.168 --> 00:47.952
And here a simple application of the chain rule will tell you that you have to propagate through the input, through the X. And you need this quantity, the gradient of the log probability with respect to its inputs.

00:49.414 --> 00:49.815
Now,

00:50.960 --> 00:59.132
As we just saw, the optimal denoising autoencoder is going to output that thing.

01:00.294 --> 01:09.768
So if we train a denoising autoencoder and we suppose it reaches a good accuracy, then we can obtain this quantity basically for free.

01:10.710 --> 01:12.192
And that's the entire trick here.

01:14.095 --> 01:16.758
So in essence, what does it mean?

01:16.798 --> 01:34.738
In essence, what it means is that if we are in our room again and we have our partial model of the world, let's say we have this model because we are here and all we've ever explored is so we've explored this, these things right here.

01:36.220 --> 01:36.500
Okay.

01:37.000 --> 01:37.521
And this.

01:39.543 --> 01:47.859
Now, when I go and do my trajectory optimization and my trajectory optimization wants to go here, I simply say, no, I don't know that.

01:47.999 --> 01:49.321
I haven't seen that yet.

01:49.401 --> 01:54.872
You can only plan basically within the space where we have already been.

01:54.932 --> 01:59.340
So you can plan like here.

01:59.320 --> 02:04.287
So here now, there is of course, there is going to be some exploration.

02:04.367 --> 02:09.435
So some probability that you can go away a bit, but not too much, right?

02:09.455 --> 02:15.584
So in this case, it would result in the planning only to happen in spaces where we've actually been.

02:15.664 --> 02:21.312
So it might go here and then here because, okay, here we haven't been anywhere.

02:21.292 --> 02:27.684
But then that would lead me to take the first step in this direction and not in this direction.

02:28.165 --> 02:36.702
And if I take my first step in this first direction, then of course, I'm going to be already a bit on the correct path right here.

02:36.742 --> 02:39.587
Whereas if I take the first step into this direction,

02:39.567 --> 02:44.295
Then after that, I'm going to have to, if once I crash here, I'm going to have to correct really hard.

02:45.096 --> 02:49.424
And that's exactly what's going to give you this super jittery control.

02:49.484 --> 02:59.080
Whereas if you only plan where you've already been, you won't, the probability that you're going to have to do like a 180 is going to be much, much lower.

03:01.444 --> 03:01.825
Okay.

03:03.568 --> 03:04.309
That seems.

